text: #COVID19vaccine. A nice primer on vaccine ‘efficacy’ vs ‘effectiveness’ by ⁦@carlzimmer⁩.  Even then, effectiveness in preventing infection does not even include ‘effectiveness’ in reducing disease burden if infected. #VaccinesWork  https://t.co/em16kQLHH4

#COVID19: Oxford vaccine shows 'encouraging' immune response in older adults. TFT 2 vaccines using 2 platforms test well in ppl >64 yo IS encouraging. The more vaccine modalities that stimulate different arms of the immune system the better. #VaccinesWork https://t.co/q7lqYYnfqL

Two #Coronavirus vaccines with ~95% efficacy; Pfizer’s is even efficacious in >65 yo. How good is this? MMR vaccine is 97% and 88% effective against measles and mumps, respectively. HepB vaccine is ~95% effective (age-dependent). Not bad if data pans out.  https://t.co/VTn9njJXPr

#Pandemic Pause. “Singing in a silent spring . . .” I 👏 the editor for allowing such a poetic title & the authors for coming up with it! Reduction of urban noise allowed birds to produce higher performance songs . . . | Birdsong during #COVID19 Shutdown😌 https://t.co/Q6siVv8jth

These #vaccines will likely receive #FDA EUA approval in the next 4 weeks making these the fastest vaccines approved. Ever. Could we have done this in 2003 had #SARS (caused by #SARSCoV "SARS1") became as widespread a pandemic as #COVID19 (aka "SARS2). Absolutely not. Why? (2/4)

Indeed! Vaccine preventable diseases also affected by #COVID19 pandemic as routine vaccinations declined. 2019 DEATHS from measles is highest in 26 years. ~208K lives lost to measles in 2019 is only slightly less than lives lost in #COVID19usa. #1Death1TooMany #VaccinesWork https://t.co/HlM6tlGKhD
